Columns.Name: MeterModelId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Meter Model.

Columns.Name: ManufacturedByPartyId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Party.

Columns.Name: FirstManufacturedDate
Columns.Description: The date that the Meter Model was first manufactured.

Columns.Name: FirstAvailableDate
Columns.Description: The date that the meter model is first available for purchase.

Columns.Name: FirstMarketedDate
Columns.Description: The date that the Meter Model was first marketed.

Columns.Name: DiscontinuedDate
Columns.Description: The date that the meter model was discontinued or abandoned.

Columns.Name: AutomaticMeterModelReaderIndicator
Columns.Description:
Indicates that the meter has AMR capabilities.

AMR (Automatic Meter Reading) and RMR (Remote Meter Reading) describe various systems that allow meters to be checked by without the need to send a meter reader out. This can be effectively achieved using off-site metering, that is an electronic meter is placed at the junction point where all the connections originate, inaccessible to the end-user, and it relays the readings via the AMR technology to the utility.

Columns.Name: RemoteMeterModelReaderIndicator
Columns.Description:
Indicates that the meter has RMR capabilities.

AMR (Automatic Meter Reading) and RMR (Remote Meter Reading) describe various systems that allow meters to be checked by without the need to send a meter reader out. This can be effectively achieved using off-site metering, that is an electronic meter is placed at the junction point where all the connections originate, inaccessible to the end-user, and it relays the readings via the AMR technology to the utility.

Columns.Name: TimeOfUseMeterModelIndicator
Columns.Description: A measuring device that records the times during which a customer uses various amounts of electricity. This type of meter is used for customers who pay time-of-use rates.

Columns.Name: MultipleTariffMeterModelIndicator
Columns.Description:
Some multiple tariff meters use different tariffs for different amounts of demand. 

These are usually industrial meters.

Columns.Name: ApplianceEnergyMeterModelIndicator
Columns.Description:
Plug in electricity meters (or "Plug load" meters) measure energy used by individual appliances.

The meter is plugged into an outlet and measures appliance energy usage.

These meters identify major energy users or devices that consume excessive standby power.

Columns.Name: SmartMeterModelIndicator
Columns.Description: Smart meters offer additional functionality including a real-time or near real-time reads, power outage notification, and power quality monitoring.

Columns.Name: PowerExportMeterModelIndicator
Columns.Description: A meter model that allows customers to own their own generating equipment and feed it back into the grid.

Columns.Name: MeterTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Meter Type.
